rdfs:label: Date time observation
rdfs:comment: A less common observation is one where the result value is a date.

rdfs:label: Hospital inpatient stay (record type)
rdfs:comment:
An entry describing the stay of a patient in hospital. As well as spcialised properties it has sub component encounters of admission and discharge.

common data model attributes for Hospital inpatient stay

rdfs:label: Team  (record type)
rdfs:comment: Teams are named groups of individuals that are linked to one or more services

rdfs:label: Medication authorisations or courses (record type)
rdfs:comment:
Also referred as Medication statement entries, these are entries for describing and authorising a course of medication or an intention to prescribe. Medication entries are precursors to the prescribing of a drug (medication order), dispensing of a drug (e.g.... chemist) or the administration of a drug (e.g.... medicine administration by nurse)

In General practice, acute prescriptions are based on medication entries with a single authorisation and repeat medications are based on medication entries with multiple authorisations. In hospital, the drug chart contains the medications.

rdfs:label: Person
rdfs:comment: An id of a person to which entries refer. A person identifier may not be 1:1 with an actual person as each organisation has there own id for example a patient id

rdfs:label: Person details
rdfs:comment: Record of the core details of  a person client patient or service covering the 'who' data and demographics

rdfs:label: Appointment  (record type)
rdfs:comment: This is information about a particular appointment. Does not include the processes involved in slot booking itself

rdfs:label: Specimen  (record type)
rdfs:comment: A specimen definition that is part of a diagnostic report

rdfs:label: Care plan  (record type)
rdfs:comment: A dynamic document that notes the plan regarding the care of a patient. As in the document structure they tend to specialise and thus this highlights only the generic sections.

rdfs:label: Problem or condition  (record type)
rdfs:comment:
Problem is a patient and record management construct designed to help manage care. The main purposes of problem structures are to highlight significant issues and to group entries in the record to enable a narrative view categorised by a focus of care. In different care domains different terms are used such as "problem", "issue" or "need" but from a structural perspective they are the same.

A problem is always associated with at least one observation and therefore automatically shares its attribution.

rdfs:label: Location  (record type)
rdfs:comment: Information about a geographical location, building or entity that is related to the organisation that operates from it. This may include a region such as a postcode area or a single property

rdfs:label: Accident and emergency encounter (record type)
rdfs:comment:
An entry recording an encounter in the A&E unit. Specialised properties.

common data model attributes for Accident and emergency encounter

rdfs:label: Numeric observation
rdfs:comment: One of the commonest observations are pathology results and they often have numeric values as results. They extend simple observations

rdfs:label: Snomed incremental counter
rdfs:comment: Class definition of the object that holds the next snomed id number when allocating Snomed extensions

rdfs:label: Allergy, intolerance and adverse reaction  (record type)
rdfs:comment:
Allergies, intolerance and adverse substance reactions are grouped together and are extensions of simple observations whereby the simple observation code includes the full concept of the allergy e.g.... "allergy to penicillin"

The additional data relates to more specific information about the substance and reaction.

rdfs:label: Referral Request or procedure request  (record type)
rdfs:comment:
A referral request or (procedure request) includes request for advice or invitation to participate in care and is not limited to conventional referrals. A referral request often precedes the encounter or care transfer that occurs subsequently. Furthermore a referral request may accompany a care transfer e.g.... a request for input from a community health professional during the discharge process. The referral type is considered as the core observation concept

Referral inherits attribution

rdfs:label: Immunisation  (record type)
rdfs:comment:
Immunisation extends a simple observation by providing more information about the immunisation procedure and vaccine used.

This is a summary of immunisation, (expected to be extended)

rdfs:label: Organisation  (record type)
rdfs:comment: A record of an organisation and its relationships. Named collections of people that have come together to achieve an objective

rdfs:label: Hospital outpatient encounter (record type)
rdfs:comment:
An entry describing a hospital outpatient attendance.

common data model attributes for Hospital outpatient encounter

rdfs:label: Encounter (record type)
rdfs:comment: An interaction between a patient (or on behalf of the patient) and a health professional or health provider. It includes consultations as well as care processes such as admission, discharges. It also includes the noting of a filing of a document or report.

rdfs:label: Appointment attendance history  (record type)
rdfs:comment: Historical Information about an actual attendance for a patient for an appointment i.e.. after the patient has arrived for appointment

rdfs:label: Critical care encounter (record type)
rdfs:comment:
An entry recording information about a criticial care encounter.

common data model attributes for Critical care encounter

rdfs:label: Device (record type)
rdfs:comment:
In the context of Discovery a device is normally used to relate to the entry of a record or in relation to its use in a procedure or operation

Devices are categorised and full defined via the information model relationships. Thus each device represents an instance of a kind of device defined in the information model

rdfs:label: Medication order or prescription (record type)
rdfs:comment: A medication order is the actual prescription for a medication item. It represents the instance of the order derived from the medication statement. It inherits MOST fields from medication and has some additional items. However, field values for the order may be different from the field values of the medication statement so they are repeated for clarity

rdfs:label: Hospital discharge (record type)
rdfs:comment:
An entry describing the event of a hospital discharge. Has specialised encounter properties.

common data model attributes for Hospital discharge (entry)

rdfs:label: Practitioner in role  (record type)
rdfs:comment:
This term refers to any person who provides care or is part of the health care process, excluding personally engaged or family carers.

A practitioner in role means a person providing care in the context of an organisation or service. The same person may have a number of roles across a number of organisations in which case it is expected that several entries may be created. This may be inferred by Discovery

rdfs:label: Appointment session  (record type)
rdfs:comment:
An appointment session is an appointment grouping implying a session or a clinic, which incorporates a number of appointments

In the Discovery model, all appointments are linked to a schedule (whether a schedule pre-authored or not) i.e.. a standalone appointment would have one schedule for the stand alone appointment

rdfs:label: Section (structural)
rdfs:comment: Section of a document or encounter with a heading

rdfs:label: Observation (record type)
rdfs:comment:
An observation is considered a type of health event that records some characteristic of the patient or some procedure performed on the patient, excluding the specialised events such as medication.

An observation in Discovery is much broader than an observation in FHIR. Because observations may be highly specialised, like encounters, only the generic properties are illustrated in this document.

The type of observation is deduced from the observation concept itself.

Observations may be linked at any level of nesting. In particular, tests and concept results observations are considered as 2 separate but linked observations, one for the test, the other for the result. This varies the Discovery observation model from the FHIR model that includes both test and result in the same observation.

For example, a blood pressure would be modelled as 3 observations as follows:

Observation 1Blood pressure

Observation 2Systolic blood pressure value= 120, part of observation 1

Observation 3Diastolic blood pressure value= 80, part of observation 2

rdfs:label: Diagnostic report components and relationships
rdfs:comment: Below are the list of common components of a diagnostic report

rdfs:label: Flag  (record type)
rdfs:comment: A flag is a warning or notification of some sort presented to the user - who may be a clinician or some other person involve in patient care. It usually represents something of sufficient significance to be warrant a special display of some sort - rather than just a note in an entry

rdfs:label: Document (record type)
rdfs:comment: A structure of a document. This is a light weight definition as documents tend to specialise very quickly to many types, even in the context of a single provider.

rdfs:label: Health record entry (record type)
rdfs:comment: An abstract class used by all person related health record entries which has a patient identifier and the organisation that is the data controller of the entry

rdfs:label: Container  (record type)
rdfs:comment: Information about a container usually used by specimens that holds a specimen

rdfs:label: Provenance activity (record type)
rdfs:comment:
In order to have generated some data, or changed some data, or deleted some data, some form of activity has taken place. This entity holds the nature of the activity that took place, points to the resulting entity and any used entities and the date and time it took place. Provenance can be illustrated by providing a timeline of all linked activities, operating as a chain going back in time.

Activities would normally be implemented using activity subtypes

rdfs:label: Hospital admission (record type)
rdfs:comment:
An entry recording the event of a hospital admission. Has specialised properties.

common data model attributes for Hospital admission

rdfs:label: Procedure  (record type)
rdfs:comment:
Procedure provides more information beyond a simple observation about an operation or observation relating to the outcome of the procedure.

Within Discovery, unlike FHIR a complex procedure description (that includes body site, laterality, method and nature of device) is represented by a Snomed expression in the observation concept.

rdfs:label: Diagnostic report  (record type)
rdfs:comment:
A diagnostic report is the set of information that is typically provided by a diagnostic service when investigations are complete. It includes a mix of component events often arranged hierarchically, some structured, some unstructured.

A diagnostic report has a header and set of components

rdfs:label: Episode of care  (record type)
rdfs:comment:
A care episode is an association between a patient and a healthcare provider during which time care is provided. The association implies that the provider has some responsibility for the provision of care during the period of time covered by the episode.

A care episode may be a concept that is explicitly stated. For example, GP registration is an explicit process by which the patient registers for care and in due course may be de-registered when they move elsewhere.

A care episode may otherwise be deduced from the data provided , usually relating to encounters. For example the acceptance of a referral or the attendance at accident and emergency provide episode of care start points. Discharge from an outpatient clinical may be used to deduce the end of a care episode.

rdfs:label: Text maps
rdfs:comment: A Collection of simple map between two pieces of text, used in various mapping utilities such as XML parsing

rdfs:label: Text map
rdfs:comment: A simple map between two pieces of text, used in various mapping utilities such as XML parsing

rdfs:label: Census output area
rdfs:comment: A geopgraphical area used in a census

rdfs:label: Object property shape
rdfs:comment: The schema for the definition of an object property

rdfs:label: Event
rdfs:comment: An entry for something that has happened or will happen at a point in time and may have a duration

rdfs:label: Workflow or scheduled event
rdfs:comment: Workflow related appointments or tasks which may be related to patients but exist independently

rdfs:label: Address (record type)
rdfs:comment: A standard mailing/postal address

rdfs:label: Contact information for an organisation or service
rdfs:comment: Data model for contact details such as email and telephone or person

rdfs:label: Activity (record type)
rdfs:comment: Processes or procedures that occur over time

rdfs:label: Business relationship (record type)
rdfs:comment: A relationship between organisations or people for business purposes e.g. Commissioning

rdfs:label: Agent
rdfs:comment: A person or organisation acting as a particular role within an organisation

rdfs:label: GP Registration status history (record type)
rdfs:comment: The history of a registration status with a general practice

rdfs:label: GP Registration(record type)
rdfs:comment: The set of registration periods with general practices

rdfs:label: Provenance agent (record type)
rdfs:comment: The agent associated with a provenance activity

rdfs:label: Provenance source entity
rdfs:comment: Information about the source entity used in a provenance activity

rdfs:label: Entry (record type)
rdfs:comment: A record entry of any kind

rdfs:label: Profile
rdfs:comment: Characteristics or features of an entity such as a patient using filters and functions on properties of the entity

rdfs:label: Match clause
rdfs:comment: A clause that matches a path to entity, its properties and its values or intersections unions or negation. Equivalent to a sparql wheew filter clause

rdfs:label: Compare clause
rdfs:comment: A clause that tests a value as equal greater or less using the results of a function to compare with the value e.g. f(age) >85

rdfs:label: Argument clause
rdfs:comment: An argument to pass into a function including the name of the parameter and the value, the value being a constant, a variable, or a match clause

rdfs:label: Range clause
rdfs:comment: Tests a value as being within a range

rdfs:label: Function clause
rdfs:comment: Clause that calls afunction passing in arguments and returning a result

rdfs:label: Entity
rdfs:comment: The shape of any class or property identified by an IRI with a name and optional description. Includes all types
